<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-628-927  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 628 927.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Government Computer News  Nov 26 1990 v9 n25 p3(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Army laptop buy hits new snag with protests.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Green, Robert.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   C3 Inc. (Contracts)Datametrics Corp. (Contracts).andO;Ticker:    CTHPV; DC.andO;Topic:     Defense ContractsUnited States. ArmyEquipment AcquisitionUnited States. General Accounting OfficeLaptop Computers.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>Army Laptop Buy Hits New Snag With ProtestsandM;Having escaped the threat last month of a possible congressional delay oftheir Lightweight Computer Unit procurement, Army officials recently hit anew snag when two companies protested the $500 million buy.andM;C3 Inc. of Herndon, Va., and Datametrics Corp. of Chatsworth, Calif., madeseparate protests to the General Accounting Office earlier this month.andP;  C3hsprotest aleges the LCU request for proposals, issued earlier this year,lacked complete evaluation criteria.andP;  Datametrics, a supplier of thermalprinters, questioned a change in the RFP concerning LCU printers.andM;Through LCU, the Army will buy as many as 20,000 ruggedized laptop copmuters,possibly 486 machines.andP;  The Army's Communications-Electronics Command inEatontown, N.J., is managing the procurement.andM;This latest hurdle follows congressional proposals that would have halted thebuy, at least temporarily.andP;  In one draft of the 1991 defense authrizationbill, Congress singled out LCU and the $100 million.andP;  Tactical Air ForceWorkstation procurement for full GAO audits.andM;But a House-Senate conference watered down the GAO review language in thefinal bill.andM;Although GAO likely will proceed with investigation of the programs, thefinal authorization bill did not prohibit contract awards pending the outcomeof the audits.andM;An Army official said last week he was not surprised when protests werefiled.andP;  &quot;When the [stricter] provision didn't make it into the final bill, aprotest was the next best way to make sure the contract was delayed,&quot; theofficial said.andM;A GAO official said the House included the first stringent provision in theauthorization bill after a bidder for both the LCU and Air Force workstationcontracts succeeded last month in persuading a member of the House Armed Services Committee to delay the buys.andP;  The early provision called for haltingthe buys until GAO completed its reviews, which lawmakers wanted done byFebruary.andO;</TEXT></DOC>